  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Edict on the Appointment of Prime Minister Choi Ja
  author: Kim Gu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When a sovereign establishes offices and ranks, it is as if constructing a tiered ladder. Those whom we raise to the highest steps must possess vast virtue and expansive wisdom, whose achievements are glorious and labors steadfast—those whose worth answers the hopes of all people. Only then do we grant them appointment.

    You, possessing talents renowned throughout the world, have undertaken the responsibilities of both civil and military affairs. By wielding the counting rods of strategy, you have subdued our enemies, brought peace to the state, and sheltered the people, so that all under heaven receive your beneficence. How could I alone defy the consensus and withhold the rewards of praise?

    Ah, the flavor of great peace fills the golden cauldron—I shall soon taste it with my own hand. You must devote yourself to the pouring and blending of this harmony.
  footnotes:
    - The 'counting rods' (算籌) refer to the instruments used in military calculation and strategy. This is a metaphor for wise governance.
    - The 'golden cauldron' (金鼎) evokes the ritual vessels of ancient sage-kings, symbolizing the abundance and harmony of a well-governed realm.
    - This edict celebrates Choi Ja's merit through the metaphor of culinary preparation, with the sovereign and minister working together to perfect the flavor of good government.
